subject: ENGLISH
text: Write a composition on any one of the following: Fashion in Dress; "Alone, alone, all, all alone, Alone on a wide, wide sea"; Contrast the characters of Queen Elizabeth and Mary, Queen of Scots; If you had to spend the rest of your life in some country other than your own, what country would you choose and why?; An Egyptian mummy comes back to life and comments on modern civilization.

subject: ENGLISH
text: Read the following passage carefully and answer the questions that follow:

subject: ENGLISH
text: What single fact shows that the Carnatic is not fertile?

subject: ENGLISH
text: What do all countries need to ensure prosperity?

subject: ENGLISH
text: What else does the Carnatic need that most other countries have by nature?

subject: ENGLISH
text: Why is this peculiarly necessary in the Carnatic?

subject: ENGLISH
text: How and by whom had this lack been supplied?

subject: ENGLISH
text: What audience is Burke addressing, and what is the general object of his speech?

subject: ENGLISH
text: Explain the metaphorical sentence "This is the national bank...irretrievably" by reference to what has gone before.

subject: ENGLISH
text: Give the exact meaning of the words in italics.

subject: ENGLISH
text: Rewrite as blank verse without changing a word or the order of the words: "I should be much for open war, O Peers, as not behind in hate, if what was urged main reason to persuade immediate war did not dissuade me most, and seem to cast ominous conjecture on the whole success."

subject: ENGLISH
text: Give a general analysis of the above sentence. Express its whole meaning in prose as briefly as you can.

subject: ENGLISH
text: Distinguish the following pairs of words and make sentences in which each word is used correctly: exorbitant and exuberant; incredible and incredulous; unpractical and impracticable; magnificent and munificent; officious and official; epitaph and epigram.

subject: ENGLISH
text: To what family of languages does English belong, and to what other languages is it most nearly akin?

subject: ENGLISH
text: Compare or contrast the two characters included in any of the following pairs: Chaucer’s Knight and Thackeray’s Colonel Newcome; Chaucer’s Clerk of Oxenford and Scott’s Dominie Sampson; Chaucer’s Good Parson and Jane Austen’s Mr. Collins; Chaucer’s Monk and Scott’s Prior Aymer.

subject: ENGLISH
text: How does Shakespeare let us know what has happened before a play begins? How does he contrive to inform us of events during the action of the play which he does not wish to present on the stage?

subject: ENGLISH
text: What metres did Milton employ in L’Allegro, Lycidas, and Paradise Lost? How does the metre in each case suit the spirit of the poem?

subject: ENGLISH
text: Paint from your reading a picture of London life in the days of Addison and Pope.

subject: ENGLISH
text: Describe Burke’s style and point out how he achieves his lofty effects.

subject: ENGLISH
text: Why are the following books famous: Percy’s Reliques of Ancient Poetry, Wordsworth and Coleridge’s Lyrical Ballads, Scott’s Minstrelsy of the Scottish Border?
